echniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n195,\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"The Theory of Constraints is a management philosophy and methodology that focuses on identifying the most important limiting factor, or constraint, that stands in the way of achieving a goal. It posits that there is always at least one constraint, often referred to as a bottleneck, that limits the achievement of a goal. The approach involves systematically improving this constraint until it is no longer the limiting factor. This methodology is used in throughput accounting to enhance performance by managing these bottlenecks effectively. Additionally, there are quizzes available that test knowledge about which statements are consistent with the Theory of Constraints.\",7\n1680,\"\"\"YAM CO\"\"\",,8\n427,\"\"\"PRODUCT B\"\"\",\"Product B is a product made and sold by Flopro, with specific costs and a selling price. It is one of the components resulting from further processing a chemical in the Daisy Co quiz. Additionally, Product B is manufactured by Yam Co. It has a selling price of $60, a raw materials cost of $2.5, a labor cost of $10, and a pressing time per unit of 0.5 hours.\",5\n426,\"\"\"PRODUCT A\"\"\",\"Product A is a versatile product associated with multiple companies. It is one of the components resulting from further processing a chemical in the Daisy Co quiz. Additionally, Product A is manufactured by Yam Co, where it has a selling price of $70, a raw materials cost of $3, a labor cost of $10, and requires 0.5 hours of pressing time per unit. Furthermore, Product A is also made and sold by Flopro, with specific costs and a selling price, although these details are not explicitly provided.\",3\n1676,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO\"\"\",\"The \"\"Throughput Accounting Ratio\"\" is a financial metric used to evaluate the efficiency of a production process. It is calculated by dividing the throughput return per hour of the bottleneck resource for a specific product, such as product B, by the overall total overhead cost per hour of the bottleneck resource. Essentially, it measures the return per hour in relation to the factory cost per hour, providing insight into how effectively the bottleneck resource is being utilized to generate profit.\",2\n1344,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput contribution per unit\"\" is calculated as the selling price per unit minus the direct material cost per unit. This metric is essential for understanding the profitability of a product by determining the contribution of each unit sold after accounting for the cost of raw materials.\",2\n420,\"\"\"FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\"\"\",\"\"\"An example where two products, G and H, are created from a joint process. G can be sold immediately after split-off, while H requires further processing. The decision to further process H is based on comparing additional revenue against additional costs.\"\"\",5\n421,\"\"\"QUIZ: FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz involves determining whether Daisy Co should further process a chemical into two components, A and B, based on their sales value and allocated costs.\"\"\",4\n417,\"\"\"JOINT PRODUCTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Joint products\"\" are two or more products that are generated simultaneously from a common input and production process. They are typically separated at the split-off point. Joint products arise when the manufacture of one product makes the manufacture of other products inevitable, and they have significant relative sales value. Costs incurred before the split-off point are joint costs and must be apportioned between the products.\",4\n1677,\"\"\"PRODUCT C\"\"\",\"\"\"Product C is one of the products manufactured by Yam Co. It has a selling price of $70, raw materials cost of $10, labour cost of $15, and pressing time per unit of 0.4 hours.\"\"\",1\n1678,\"\"\"PRODUCT D\"\"\",\"\"\"Product D is a fourth product made by Yam Co. It has a throughput accounting ratio of less than one, indicating it may not be profitable under current conditions.\"\"\",1\n1675,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION PER HOUR OF PRESSING TIME\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput contribution per hour of pressing time is calculated by dividing the throughput contribution per unit by the pressing time per unit.\"\"\",1\n1350,\"\"\"BOTTLENECK IDENTIFICATION QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves identifying the bottleneck process in a manufacturing scenario with three consecutive processes: preparation, machining, and polishing. It requires calculating the maximum weekly output for each process to determine the bottleneck.\"\"\",1\n1679,\"\"\"OPTIMAL SUIT PRODUCTION STRATEGY AND RESOURCE ALLOCATION FOR CUT AND STITCH\"\"\",\"\"\"Cut and Stitch (CS) make two types of suits using skilled tailors (labour) and a delicate and unique fabric (material). Both the tailors and the fabric are in short supply, and the accountant at CS has produced a linear programming model to help decide the optimal production mix. The model includes variables for work suits and lounge suits, an objective to maximize contribution, and constraints related to tailors' time, fabric, and production limits. The feasible region and optimal point are identified on a graph, with point B being the optimal point where contribution is maximized. The case involves determining the optimal production strategy and resource allocation.\"\"\",1\n1248,\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS QUIZ\"\"\",\"The \"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS QUIZ\"\" is designed to test knowledge on the theory of constraints, with a particular focus on managing bottlenecks and maximizing throughput contribution. It assesses understanding by evaluating the ability to identify bottlenecks in production and the appropriate operation of non-bottleneck resources.\",1\n425,\"\"\"PRODUCT H\"\"\",\"Product H is a product with the second highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product I until the limiting factor is used up. It is one of the products created from a joint process and requires further processing before it can be sold.\",2\n419,\"\"\"SPLIT-OFF POINT (SOP)\"\"\",\"\"\"The split-off point is the stage in the production process where products produced are not separately identifiable until this point. Costs incurred before the SOP are joint costs.\"\"\",2\n2047,\"\"\"MAXIMIZING NET PROFIT AND THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING ANALYSIS FOR PRODUCTS A AND B\"\"\",\"\"\"Flopro makes and sells two products, A and B, each passing through the same automated production operations. The case involves analyzing the profitability and throughput accounting for these products.\"\"\",2\n1704,\"\"\"PRODUCTION CONSTRAINTS FOR PRODUCT B AND T\"\"\",\"\"\"The production constraints for Product B and T are given by the formulas: Materials: 2B + 3T = 2000, Labour: 3B + 5T = 3200.\"\"\",2\n1709,\"\"\"TOTAL CONTRIBUTION FROM PRODUCTS B AND T IN APRIL\"\"\",\"\"\"The total contribution from Products B and T in April is calculated using simultaneous equations: Total contribution = ($37 * 400) + ($52 * 400) = $35,600.\"\"\",2\n424,\"\"\"PRODUCT G\"\"\",\"\"\"Product G is one of the products created from a joint process and can be sold immediately after the split-off point.\"\"\",1\n433,\"\"\"SPLIT-OFF POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"The split-off point is the stage in the production process where joint products can be recognized as separate products. Costs incurred up to this point are considered common costs.\"\"\",2\n601,\"\"\"MAXIMUM CONTRIBUTION CALCULATION\"\"\",\"\"\"The maximum contribution is calculated by prioritizing products based on their contribution per limiting factor and producing them up to their maximum demand or until the limiting factor is exhausted.\"\"\",4\n1701,\"\"\"PRODUCT T\"\"\",\"\"\"Product T is another product manufactured, with a standard cost card detailing its selling price, direct materials, direct labour, variable overheads, fixed overheads, and profit.\"\"\",4\n418,\"\"\"BY-PRODUCTS\"\"\",\"\"\"By-products are produced alongside one or more main products but have a small relative sales value. They are unlikely to influence the decision to produce the main products.\"\"\",1\n609,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION PER LIMITING FACTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"Contribution per limiting factor is calculated by dividing the contribution margin of a product by the amount of the limiting factor required to produce one unit of the product.\"\"\",1\n1708,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT OF LIMITING FACTOR FOR PRODUCT T\"\"\",\"\"\"The contribution per unit of limiting factor for Product T is calculated as follows: Contribution per kg = $52 / 3 = $17.33.\"\"\",1\n423,\"\"\"DAISY CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Daisy Co is the company involved in the further processing decision quiz.\"\"\",1\n607,\"\"\"PRODUCT J\"\"\",\"\"\"Product J is a product with the third highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product H until the limiting factor is used up.\"\"\",1\n608,\"\"\"PRODUCT K\"\"\",\"\"\"Product K is a product with the fourth highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product J until the limiting factor is used up.\"\"\",1\n1703,\"\"\"STANDARD COST CARD FOR PRODUCT T\"\"\",\"\"\"The standard cost card for Product T includes the following details: Selling price: $120, Direct materials: $15, Direct labour: $35, Variable overheads: $18, Fixed overheads: $10, Profit: $42.\"\"\",1\n2051,\"\"\"BOTTLENECK HOURS\"\"\",\"\"\"Bottleneck hours refer to the limited hours available for production due to constraints in the production process.\"\"\",1\n437,\"\"\"COMMON COST\"\"\",,1\n1345,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT OF LIMITING FACTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"Throughput contribution per unit of limiting factor = Throughput contribution per unit / Units of limiting factor (minutes)\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n217,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING\"\"\",\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Theory of constraints is applied in throughput accounting to improve production efficiency.\"\"\",19\n246,\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"YAM CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Yam Co applies the Theory of Constraints to optimize its production process.\"\"\",15\n245,\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz about the theory of constraints is related to the concept of the theory of constraints.\"\"\",14\n416,\"\"\"PRODUCT B\"\"\",\"\"\"YAM CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Product B is one of the products manufactured by Yam Co.\"\"\",13\n414,\"\"\"PRODUCT A\"\"\",\"\"\"YAM CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Product A is one of the products manufactured by Yam Co.\"\"\",11\n1570,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO\"\"\",\"\"\"YAM CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Yam Co uses throughput accounting ratio to assess the efficiency of its production processes.\"\"\",10\n1310,\"\"\"THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT\"\"\",\"\"\"YAM CO\"\"\",\"\"\"Yam Co calculates throughput contribution per unit to determine profitability of each product.\"\"\",10\n407,\"\"\"FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\"\"\",\"\"\"QUIZ: FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\"\"\",\"\"\"The quiz on further processing decision is based on the example of further processing decision provided.\"\"\",9\n404,\"\"\"JOINT PRODUCTS\"\"\",\"\"\"FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\"\"\",\"\"\"Further processing decisions involve joint products created from the same production process.\"\"\",9\n412,\"\"\"QUIZ: FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION\"\"\",\"\"\"PRODUCT B\"\"\",\"\"\"Product B is one of the components resulting from fu